# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abortion-in-the-netherlands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] An **abortifacient** ("that which will cause a miscarriage" from Latin: *abortus* "miscarriage" and *faciens* "making") is a substance that induces abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] This is a nonspecific term which may refer to any number of substances or medications, ranging from herbs to prescription medications.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Common abortifacients used in performing medical abortions include mifepristone, which is typically used in conjunction with misoprostol in a two-step approach.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Synthetic oxytocin, which is routinely used safely during term labor, is also commonly used to induce abortion in the second or third trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] For thousands of years, writers in many parts of the world have described and recommended herbal abortifacients to women who seek to terminate a pregnancy, although their use may carry risks to the health of the woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Because "abortifacient" is a broad term used to describe a substance's effects on pregnancy, there is a wide range of drugs that can be described as abortifacients or as having abortifacient properties.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The most commonly recommended medication regimen for intentionally inducing abortion involves the use of mifepristone followed by misoprostol one to two days later.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The use of these medications for the purpose of ending a pregnancy has been extensively studied, and has been shown to be both effective and safe with fewer than 0.4% of patients needing hospitalization to treat an infection or to receive a blood transfusion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] This combination is approved for use up to 10 weeks' gestation (70 days after the start of the last menstrual period).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Other drugs with abortifacient properties can have multiple uses.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Both synthetic oxytocin (Pitocin) and dinoprostone (Cervidil, Prepidil) are routinely used during healthy, term labor.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Pitocin is used to induce and strengthen contractions, and Cervidil is used to prepare the cervix for labor by inducing softening and widening of this opening to the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] When used this way, neither medication is considered an abortifacient.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] However, the same drugs can be used to induce an abortion, particularly after 12 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Misoprostol (discussed above) is also used to treat peptic ulcers in patients who have had gastric or intestinal damage from use of NSAIDs.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Because its use in treatment of ulcers makes it easier to access, misoprostol alone is sometimes used for self-induced abortion in countries or regions where legal abortion is not available or readily accessible.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Not all abortifacient agents are taken with the intention to end a pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Methotrexate, a drug often used for management of rheumatoid arthritis, can induce abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] For this reason contraception is often advised while using methotrexate for management of a chronic condition.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Sometimes herbs or herbal medicines are used in an attempt to induce abortion; use of such substances as abortifacients is dangerous, can cause serious‍— even lethal‍— side effects, and is not recommended by physicians.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] In general, a dose sufficient to be effective poses a risk to the mother because of potential liver and kidney damage; failed attempts may require a follow-up clinical abortion because the uterus did not evacuate completely.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Modern users often lack knowledge of the traditional methods of preparation and use of these substances.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Riddle called these circumstances a "broken chain of knowledge", one he attributed to the historic persecution of women acting as witches, midwives, or wisewomen who had knowledge of such practices.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] In ancient Babylonian texts, scholars have described multiple written prescriptions or instructions for ending pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Some of these instructions were explicitly for ingesting ingredients to end a pregnancy, whereas other cuneiform texts discuss the ingestion of ingredients to return a missed menstrual period (which is used repeatedly throughout history as a coded reference to abortion).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The ancient Greek colony of Cyrene at one time had an economy based almost entirely on the production and export of the plant silphium, which had uses ranging from food to a salve for feral dog bites.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] It was also considered a powerful abortifacient used to "purge the uterus".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Silphium figured so prominently in the wealth of Cyrene that the plant appeared on coins minted there.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] In the Bible, Biblical scholars and learned Biblical commentators view the ordeal of the bitter water (prescribed for a *sotah*, or a wife whose husband suspects that she was unfaithful to him) as referring to the use of abortifacients to terminate her pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The wife drinks "water of bitterness," which, if she is guilty, causes the abortion or miscarriage of a pregnancy she may be carrying.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The Biblical scholar Tikva Frymer-Kensky has disputed the interpretation that the ordeal of the bitter water referred to the use of abortifacients.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The medieval Islamic physician Ibn Sina documented various birth control practices, including the use of rue as an abortifacient.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Similarly, 11th-century physician Constantine the African described multiple abortifacient herbs, which he classified by order of their intensity, starting with abortifacients that had weaker effects on the body and ending with the most potent substances.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Carl Linnaeus, known as the "father of botany", listed five abortifacients in his 1749 *Materia medica*.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] For Aboriginal people in Australia, plants such as giant boat-lip orchid (*Cymbidium madidum*), quinine bush (*Petalostigma pubescens*), or blue-leaved mallee (*Eucalyptus gamophylla*) were ingested, inserted into the body, or were smoked with Cooktown ironwood (*Erythrophleum chlorostachys*).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Historically, the First Nations people of eastern Canada used *Sanguinaria canadensis* (bloodwort) and *Juniperus virginiana* to induce abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] According to Virgil Vogel, a historian of the indigenous societies of North America, the Ojibwe used blue cohosh (*Caulophyllum thalictroides*) as an abortifacient, and the Quinault used thistle for the same purpose.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] The appendix to Vogel's book lists red cedar (*Juniperus virginiana*), American pennyroyal (*Hedeoma pulegioides*), tansy, Canada wild ginger (*Asarum canadense*), and several other herbs as abortifacients used by various North American Indian tribes.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Following a tradition among European and English authors, colonial Americans were advised by Benjamin Franklin to use careful measurements in his recipe for an abortifacient that he used as an example in a book he published to teach mathematics and many useful skills.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] During the American slavery period, 18th and 19th centuries, cotton root bark was used in folk remedies to induce a miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] In the late 19th century, women in the UK and US increasingly ingested lead to abort pregnancies, sometimes in the form of pills made of diachylon or lead plaster.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] It would often cause the women to become ill and could kill them.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] In the 19th century Madame Restell provided mail-order abortifacients and surgical abortion to pregnant clients in New York.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortifacient] Early 20th-century newspaper advertisements included coded advertisements for abortifacient substances which would solve menstrual "irregularities" .
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Scientific and medical expert bodies have repeatedly concluded that abortion poses no greater mental health risks than carrying an unintended pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Nevertheless, the relationship between induced **abortion and mental health** is an area of political controversy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] In 2008, the American Psychological Association concluded after a review of available evidence that induced abortion did not increase the risk of mental-health problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health similarly concluded that first-time abortion in the first trimester does not increase the risk of mental-health problems compared with bringing the pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] In 2018, The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine concluded that abortion does not lead to depression, anxiety, or post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists likewise summarized the evidence by finding that abortion did not increase the risk of mental-health problems compared to women carrying an unwanted pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Two studies conducted on the Danish population in 2011 and 2012 analysed the association between abortion and psychiatric admission found no increase in admissions after an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] The same study, in fact, found an increase in psychiatric admission after first child-birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] A 2008 systematic review of the medical literature on abortion and mental health found that high-quality studies consistently showed few or no mental-health consequences of abortion, while poor-quality studies were more likely to report negative consequences.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Despite the weight of scientific and medical opinion, some anti-abortion advocacy groups have continued to allege a link between abortion and mental-health problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Some anti-abortion groups have used the term "post-abortion syndrome" to refer to negative psychological effects which they attribute to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] However, "post-abortion syndrome" is not recognized as an actual syndrome by the mainstream medical community.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Post-abortion syndrome (PAS) is not included in the *Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders* DSM-IV-TR or in the ICD-10 list of psychiatric conditions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Medical professionals and pro-choice advocates have argued that the effort to popularize the idea of a "post-abortion syndrome" is a tactic used by anti-abortion advocates for political purposes.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Some U.S. state legislatures have mandated that patients be told that abortion increases their risk of depression and suicide, despite the scientific evidence contradicting such claims.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Systematic reviews of the scientific literature have concluded that there are no differences in the long-term mental health of women who obtain induced abortions as compared to women in appropriate control groups—that is, those who carry unplanned pregnancies to term.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] These studies have consistently found no causal relationship between abortion and mental-health problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] The correlations observed in some studies may be explained by pre-existing social circumstances and emotional or mental health problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Various factors, such as emotional attachment to the pregnancy, lack of support, and conservative views on abortion may increase the likelihood of experiencing negative reactions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Major medical and psychiatric expert groups have consistently found that abortion does not cause mental-health problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] In 2008, the American Psychological Association reviewed the literature on abortion and mental health and concluded that the risk of mental health problems following a single, first-trimester induced abortion of an adult women is no greater than carrying an unwanted pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Since these and other risk factors may also predispose some women to more negative reactions following a birth, the higher rates of mental illness observed among women with a prior history of abortion are more likely to be caused by these other factors than by abortion itself.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] The panel noted severe inconsistency between the outcomes reported by studies on the effect of multiple abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Additionally, the same factors which predispose a woman to multiple unwanted pregnancies may also predispose her to mental health difficulties.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Therefore, they declined to draw a firm conclusion on studies concerning multiple abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Royal College of Psychiatrists undertook a systematic review to clarify the question of whether abortion had harmful effects on women's mental health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] The review, conducted by the National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health and funded by the U.K.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Department of Health, concluded that while unwanted pregnancy may increase the risk of mental-health problems, women faced with unwanted pregnancies have similar rates of mental-health problems whether they choose to carry the pregnancy to term or to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Some women do experience negative emotions after an abortion, but not at rates different from women who wanted an abortion and did not have one or from women who have miscarriages.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Women having abortions may receive support from abortion providers, or national call centers like Exhale.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] The idea that abortion has negative psychological effects was widely promoted by crisis pregnancy centers in the 1970s and the term "post-abortion syndrome" has widely been used by anti-abortion advocates to broadly include any negative emotional reactions attributed to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] The Guttmacher Institute reports that as of August 2018, of the 22 U.S. states that include information on possible psychological responses to abortion, eight states stress negative emotional responses.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Under the 1967 Abortion Act, abortion in the United Kingdom was legalized only when two doctors agreed that carrying the pregnancy to term would be detrimental to a woman's physical or mental health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Consideration of mental health also played a role in the 1973 U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Wade* which ruled that state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the [woman's] life or health".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Everett Koop, an evangelical Christian and abortion opponent, to issue a report on the health effects of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Reportedly, the idea for the review was conceived as a political gambit by Reagan advisors Dinesh D'Souza and Gary Bauer, who believed that such a report would "rejuvenate" the anti-abortion movement by producing evidence of the risks of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Koop was reluctant to accept the assignment, believing that Reagan was more concerned with appeasing his political base than with improving women's health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Koop ultimately reviewed over 250 studies pertaining to the psychological impact of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Wade*." In later testimony before the United States Congress, Koop stated that the quality of existing evidence was too poor to prepare a report that "could withstand scientific and statistical scrutiny".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Subsequently, a Congressional committee charged that Koop refused to publish the results of his review because he failed to find evidence that abortion was harmful, and that Koop watered down his findings in his letter to Reagan by claiming that the studies were inconclusive.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] Later in 1989, responding to the political debate over the question, the American Psychological Association (APA) undertook a review of the scientific literature.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] In 2006, the U.K.'s House of Commons Science and Technology Committee undertook another inquiry into scientific developments and included a request for the RCP to update their 1994 statement on abortion in light of more recent studies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] In 2008, the RCP did update their position statement to recommend that women should be screened for risk factors that may be associated with subsequent development of mental health problems and should be counselled about the possible mental health risks of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-and-mental-health] This recommendation resulted in the 2011 review conducted by the National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The **abortion debate** is a longstanding and contentious discourse that touches on the moral, legal, medical, and religious aspects of induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In English-speaking countries, the debate has two major sides, commonly referred to as the "pro-choice" and "pro-life" movements.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Generally, supporters of *pro-choice* argue for the right to choose to terminate a pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] They take into account various factors such as the stage of fetal development, the health of the woman, and the circumstances of the conception.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] By comparison, the supporters of *pro-life* generally argue that a fetus is a human being with inherent rights and intrinsic value, and thus, cannot be overridden by the woman's choice or circumstances and that abortion is morally wrong in most or all cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Both the terms *pro-choice* and *pro-life* are considered loaded words in mainstream media, which tend to prefer terms such as "abortion rights" or "anti-abortion" as more neutral and avoidant of bias.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Each movement has had varying results in influencing public opinion and attaining legal support for its position.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Supporters and opponents of abortion often argue that it is essentially a moral issue, concerning the beginning of human personhood, rights of the fetus, and bodily integrity.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Additionally, some argue that government involvement in abortion-related decisions, particularly through public funding, raises ethical and political questions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Libertarians, for example, may oppose taxpayer funding for abortion based on principles of limited government and personal responsibility, while holding diverse views on the legality of the procedure itself.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The debate has become a political and legal issue in some countries with those who oppose abortion seeking to enact, maintain, and expand anti-abortion laws, while those who support abortion seek to repeal or ease such laws and expand access to the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Abortion laws vary considerably between jurisdictions, ranging from outright prohibition of the procedure to public funding of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The availability of abortion procedures considered safe also varies across the world and exists mainly in places that legalize abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In ancient times, issues such as abortion and infanticide were evaluated by patriarchies within the contexts of family planning, gender selection, population control, and property rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The rights of the prospective mother and child were typically not central to these considerations.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Ancient discourse often expressed the concerns on the nature of humankind, the existence of a soul, when life begins, and the beginning of human personhood, issues that are still relevant even today.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Discussion of the presumed personhood of a fetus may be complicated by the current legal status of children.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Similar to minors, fetuses and embryos lack certain legal capacities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In many legal systems, a fetus or an embryo does not have the same legal status as a person.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] They have not reached the age of majority and deemed not able to enter into contracts and to sue or be sued.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Since the 1860s, they have been treated as persons for the limited purposes of offence against the person law in the UK including Northern Ireland, although this treatment was amended by the Abortion Act of 1967 in England, Scotland, and Wales.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In America, there have been logistical challenges in considering a fetus as a person.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some legal interpretations have argued that if a fetus is considered a person, then it is only under certain conditions as it relies on the body of another person and is usually not the object of direct action by another person.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In the current debate, proposals range from prohibitions on abortion in all cases, even when the woman's life is at risk, to calls for complete legalization with provisions for public funding.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Many of the terms used in the debate are seen as political framing: terms used to validate one's stance while invalidating the opposition's.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] For example, the labels "pro-choice" and "pro-life" imply widely held values such as liberty or the right to life, while suggesting that the opposition must be "anti-choice" or "anti-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Terms used in the debate to describe their opponents consist of "pro-abortion", "pro-abort"; however, these terms do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Another identifier in the debate is "abolitionist", which harks back to the 19th-century struggle against human slavery.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Francis Beckwith argues that even seemingly neutral phrases like "abortion rights" are ideologically loaded.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] He contends that such language presupposes the moral legitimacy of abortion by framing it as a fundamental right, thereby sidestepping the underlying philosophical question of whether the unborn possess a right to life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In doing so, the term shapes public discourse by implicitly framing abortion access as presumptively justified.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Appeals are often made in the abortion debate to the rights of the fetus, pregnant woman, or other parties.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Such appeals can generate confusion if the *type* of rights is not specified (whether civil, natural, or otherwise) or if it is simply *assumed* that the right appealed to takes precedence over all other competing rights (an example of begging the question).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The appropriate terms to designate the human organism before birth are also debated.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some anti-abortion supporters regard the technical terminology "embryo" and "fetus" as dehumanizing, whereas some abortion rights proponents regard ordinary terms such as "baby" or "child" as emotion-inducing.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The use of the term "baby" to describe the unborn human organism is seen by some scholars as part of an effort to assign the organism agency, functioning to further the construction of fetal personhood.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Anti-abortion activists occasionally use the term "the silent holocaust" or "the American genocide" about the number of abortions that have been performed in the United States since 1973.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] There is abundant debate regarding the extent of abortion regulation by the government.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Supporters of abortion rights may argue against the government regulation of abortions, and rather it be treated as routine medical practice.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] From a compromising perspective, both sides may support the permission of the government to prohibit elective abortions after the 20th week, viability, or the second trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Religion has also played a role in the debate.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] For example, some Christian denominations and groups generally oppose abortion, believing it more aligns with their interpretation of the Bible, and because of this may support the prohibition of some or all abortions, starting from conception.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Those who oppose abortion rights may argue against the procedures and nature of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The two sides of the political debate represent the contentious moral principles in the "sanctity of life" versus "the woman's right to choose." Abortion debates differ from other public health issues due to complex ethical and legal considerations.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In popular culture, the American romantic drama dance film *Dirty Dancing* (1987) is seen by *The Hollywood Reporter* as "a clear and unapologetic argument for reproductive choice".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Abortion and contraception were completely banned in Romania from 1967 to 1989, due to Decree 770 under Romanian dictator Nicolae Ceaușescu.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] As a result, maternal mortality in Romania became the highest in Europe, and thousands of children ended up in orphanages raised in grievous conditions, leading to a rise in child mortality.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] As of 2016, six countries completely outlaw abortion: El Salvador, Malta, Vatican City, the Dominican Republic, Philippines, and Nicaragua.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] This prohibits a woman from having an abortion for any reason (underage, fetal impairment, rape/incest), even if it might mean saving her life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] For example, in El Salvador, abortions are punishable with up to 50 years in prison.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Argentina allowed abortion only in case of rape or if the woman's health was at risk.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In December 2020, the Argentine Senate passed a bill to legalize abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Also in 2020, the Constitutional Tribunal ended almost all legal abortion in Poland.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] China has a free abortion policy but some studies show that its government also uses forced abortion to enforce strict limits on how many children each family can have.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In the United States, there are increasing efforts to limit access to abortion by states in the wake of the 2022 reversal of Roe v Wade (1973) which allowed for a constitutional right to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Abortion rights advocates argue that outlawing abortion increases the rate of unsafe abortions, as the availability of professional abortion services decreases, and leads to increased maternal mortality.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] According to a global study collaboratively conducted by the World Health Organization and the Guttmacher Institute, most unsafe abortions occur where abortion is illegal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Withholding access to safe abortions results in 30,000 abortion-related deaths per year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Women may also choose suicide when abortion is illegal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The effect on crime of legalized abortion is a subject of controversy, with proponents of the theory generally arguing that "unwanted children" are more likely to become criminals and that an inverse correlation is observed between the availability of abortion and subsequent crime.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] KFF conducted a nationally representative survey of office-based OBGYNs in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Since Dobbs, 42% of OBGYNs report that they are very or somewhat concerned about their own legal risk when making decisions about patient care and abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] This could greatly affect how many OBGYNs will continue to practice.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] As an example of political decisions concerning the abortion debate, in the years following the *Dobbs* ruling, state governments have been granted political authority over abortion access and resources.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The issue-framing and policy-making aspects vary from each perspective and interest but ultimately form the strategic decisions for legislators for support or opposition to their efforts.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The *Dobbs* decision allows other debates to form over several different concepts in other state legislature concerning the terms "privacy" and "liberty interests" which those cases have determined the foundation of clinician-patient relationships and private medical decisions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Abortion decisions bring focus onto other state efforts corresponding to abortion, such as limiting access to medication abortions, preventing third parties from assisting anyone seeking an abortion, or punishing women who get abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In the United States, the debate has been framed as an aspect of privacy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Even though the right to privacy is not explicitly stated in many constitutions of sovereign nations, many people see it as foundational to a functioning democracy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Traditionally, American courts have located the right to privacy in the Fourth Amendment, Ninth Amendment, Fourteenth Amendment, as well as the penumbra of the Bill of Rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The landmark decision *Roe v Wade* relied on the 14th Amendment, which guarantees that federal rights shall be applied equally to all persons born in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The 14th Amendment has given rise to the doctrine of Substantive due process, which is said to guarantee various privacy rights, including the right to bodily integrity.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] While governments are allowed to invade the privacy of their citizens in some cases, they are expected to protect privacy in all cases lacking a compelling state interest.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In the US, the compelling state interest test has been developed per the standards of strict scrutiny.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In *Roe v Wade*, the Court decided that the state has an "important and legitimate interest in protecting the potentiality of human life" from the point of viability on, but that before viability, the woman's fundamental rights are more compelling than that of the state.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] After the court ruling, controversies continued, sometimes passionately.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Judith Blake, for example, even before the ruling, predicted a backlash in attitudes about abortion in "Abortion and Public Opinion" (1971).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] After the ruling, her research indicated a considerable discrepancy between the views of the Court and those of the public at large.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Meanwhile, philosophers and theologians (including Roger Wertheimer and Edmund Pincoffs) debated questions such as whether there is any rational basis for deciding whether a zygote, embryo, or fetus must be considered to be a human being.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Justice Potter Stewart, who joined with the majority, viewed the *Roe* opinion as "legislative" and asked that more consideration be paid to state legislatures.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Candidates competing for the Democratic nomination for the 2008 presidential election cited *Gonzales v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In upholding the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act, *Carhart* is the first judicial opinion upholding a legal barrier to a specific abortion procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] — Majority opinion of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] — Justice Antonin Scalia, "concurring in the judgment in part and dissenting in part".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Although there is a general presumption against a state's ability to regulate extraterritorially (i.e., beyond its borders), legal authority suggests that the Constitution does not prohibit a state from regulating abortion travel.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Morgentaler*, a 5–2 majority of the Supreme Court of Canada held that the abortion provisions of the Criminal Code were unconstitutional.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The majority of the Court held that the abortion provisions infringed the rights of pregnant women, contrary to the security of the person clause of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, and could not be justified.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The only laws currently governing abortion in Canada are those that govern medical procedures in general, such as those regulating the licensing of facilities, the training of medical personnel, and the like.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Laws also exist which are intended to prevent anti-abortion activists from interfering with staff and patient access to hospitals and clinics, for instance by creating buffer zones around them.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Because the courts did not establish abortion as a constitutional right, Parliament continues to have jurisdiction to legislate concerning abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The Progressive Conservative government of Brian Mulroney twice attempted to do.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The first bill, introduced in 1988, was defeated in the House of Commons.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The next year, in 1989, the Mulroney government introduced a bill that would allow abortion only if two doctors certified that the woman's health was in danger.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] This bill passed the House of Commons but was defeated by a tie vote in the Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] There have not been any further government attempts to enact legislation relating to abortion in Parliament since then.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Although the courts have not ruled on the question of fetal personhood as a matter of constitutional law, the question has been raised in two cases, *Tremblay v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Both cases relied on the born alive rule, part of Canadian common law and Quebec civil law, to determine that the fetus was not a person by law.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Two further cases are notable: *Dobson (Litigation Guardian of) v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Dobson*, and *Winnipeg Child & Family Services (Northwest Area) v G.(D.F.)*, which dismissed fetal abuse claims.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] A 2005 multidisciplinary systematic review in *JAMA* in the area of fetal development found that a fetus is unlikely to feel pain until after the sixth month of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Developmental neurobiologists suspect that the establishment of thalamocortical connections (at about 26 weeks) may be critical to fetal perception of pain.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] However, legislation was proposed by anti-abortion advocates that would require abortion providers to tell a woman that the fetus may feel pain during an abortion procedure if the woman's proposed abortion was at least 20 weeks after fertilization.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The *JAMA* review concluded that data from dozens of medical reports and studies indicate that fetuses are unlikely to feel pain until the third trimester of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] However several medical critics have since disputed these conclusions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Other researchers such as Anand and Fisk have challenged the idea that pain cannot be felt before 26 weeks, positing instead that pain can be felt at around 20 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Anand's suggestion is disputed in a March 2010 report on fetal awareness published by a working party of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG), citing a lack of evidence or rationale.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Page 20 of the report definitively states that the fetus cannot feel pain before week 24.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Because pain can involve sensory, emotional and cognitive factors, leaving it "impossible to know" when painful experiences are perceived, even if it is known when thalamocortical connections are established.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Wendy Savage—former press officer, Doctors for a Woman's Choice on Abortion—considered the question to be irrelevant.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In a 1997 letter to the *British Medical Journal*, she noted that the majority of surgical abortions in Britain were performed under general anesthesia which affects the fetus, and considers the discussion "to be unhelpful to women and to the scientific debate".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Others caution against the unnecessary use of fetal anesthetic during abortion, as it poses potential health risks to the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] David Mellor and colleagues have noted that the fetal brain is already awash in naturally occurring chemicals that keep it sedated and anesthetized until birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] At least one anesthesia researcher has suggested the fetal pain legislation may make abortions harder to obtain because abortion clinics lack the equipment and expertise to supply fetal anesthesia.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Anesthesia is administered directly to fetuses only while they are undergoing surgery.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] There are differences of opinion as to whether a zygote/embryo/fetus acquires "personhood" or was always a "person".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] If "personhood" is acquired, opinions differ about when this happens.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Traditionally, the concept of personhood entailed the soul, a metaphysical concept referring to a non-corporeal or extra-corporeal dimension of human being.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Today, the concepts of subjectivity and intersubjectivity, personhood, mind, and self have come to encompass several aspects of human beings previously considered the domain of the "soul".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Thus, while the historical question has been: when does the soul enter the body, in modern terms, the question could be put instead: at what point does the developing individual develop personhood or selfhood?
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Since human development occurs continuously, identifying a precise time when a human being becomes a person could lead to an instance of the Sorites paradox (also known as *the paradox of the heap*).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Related issues attached to the question of the beginning of human personhood include the legal status, and subjectivity of the pregnant woman and the philosophical concept of "natality" (i.e.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] "the distinctively human capacity to initiate a new beginning", which a new human life embodies).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Although the two main sides of the abortion debate tend to agree that a human fetus is biologically and genetically human (that is, of the human species), they often differ in their view on whether or not a human fetus is, in any of various ways, a *person*.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Anti-abortion supporters argue that abortion is morally wrong on the basis that a fetus is an innocent human person or because a fetus is a potential life that will, in most cases, develop into a fully functional human being.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] They believe that a fetus is a person upon conception.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Others reject this position by distinguishing between *human being* and *human person*, arguing that while the fetus is *innocent* and *biologically human*, it is not a *person* with a *right to life*.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] In support of this distinction, some propose a list of criteria as markers of personhood.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] For example, Mary Ann Warren suggests consciousness (at least the capacity to feel pain), reasoning, self-motivation, the ability to communicate, and self-awareness.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] According to Warren, a being need not exhibit all of these criteria to qualify as a person with a right to life, but if a being exhibits *none* of them (or perhaps only one), then it is certainly not a person.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Warren concludes that as the fetus satisfies only one criterion, consciousness (and this only after it becomes susceptible to pain), the fetus is not a person and abortion is therefore morally permissible.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Other philosophers apply similar criteria, concluding that a fetus lacks a right to life because it lacks brain waves or higher brain function, self-consciousness, rationality, and autonomy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] These lists diverge over precisely *which* features confer a right to life, but tend to propose various *developed* psychological or physiological features not found in fetuses.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Critics of this typically argue that some of the proposed criteria for personhood would disqualify two classes of *born* human beings – reversibly comatose patients, and human infants – from having a right to life, since they, like fetuses, are not self-conscious, do not communicate, and so on.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Defenders of the proposed criteria may respond that the reversibly comatose *do* satisfy the relevant criteria because they "retain all their *unconscious* mental states". or at least some higher brain function (brain waves).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] An alternative approach is to base personhood or the right to life on a being's *natural* or *inherent* capacities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] On this approach, a being essentially has a right to life if it has a *natural capacity* to develop the relevant psychological features; and, since human beings do have this natural capacity, they essentially have a right to life beginning at conception (or whenever they come into existence).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Respondents to this criticism argue that the noted human cases in fact would not be classified as persons as they do not have a natural capacity to develop any psychological features.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Also, in a view that favors benefiting even unconceived but potential future persons, it has been argued as justified to abort an unintended pregnancy in favor for conceiving a new child later in better conditions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Philosophers such as Aquinas use the concept of individuation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] They argue that abortion is not permissible from the point at which individual human identity is realized.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Since division of the zygote into twins through the process of monozygotic twinning can occur until the fourteenth day of pregnancy, Kenny argues that individual identity is obtained at this point and thus abortion is not permissible after two weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Thomson's variant of this argument draws an analogy between forcing a woman to continue an unwanted pregnancy and forcing a person to allow his body to be used to maintain blood homeostasis (as a dialysis machine is used) for another person with kidney failure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] It is argued that just as it would be permissible to "unplug" and thereby cause the death of the person who is using one's kidneys, so it is permissible to abort the fetus (who similarly, it is said, has no right to use one's body's life-support functions against one's will).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Critics of this argument generally argue that there are morally relevant disanalogies between abortion and the kidney failure scenario.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some writers defend the analogy against these objections, arguing that the disanalogies are morally irrelevant or do not apply to abortion in the way critics have claimed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Alternative scenarios have been put forth as more accurate and realistic representations of the moral issues present in abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] John Noonan proposes the scenario of a family who was found to be liable for frostbite finger loss suffered by a dinner guest whom they refused to allow to stay overnight, although it was very cold outside and the guest showed signs of being sick.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Noonan argues that just as it would not be permissible to refuse temporary accommodation for the guest to protect him from physical harm, it would not be permissible to refuse temporary accommodation for a fetus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Other critics claim that there is a difference between artificial and extraordinary means of preservation, such as medical treatment, kidney dialysis, and blood transfusions, and normal and natural means of preservation, such as gestation, childbirth, and breastfeeding.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] They argue that if a baby was born into an environment in which there was no replacement available for her mother's breast milk, and the baby would either breastfeed or starve, the mother would have to allow the baby to breastfeed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] But the mother would never have to give the baby a blood transfusion, no matter what the circumstances were.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The difference between breastfeeding in that scenario and blood transfusions is the difference between using one's body as a kidney dialysis machine, and gestation and childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Arguments in support of this classification often cite considerations such as the need for consistent public policy, the potential harms of criminalizing abortion, and the unequal distribution of reproductive healthcare access.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Other critics counter that framing abortion access as the primary means to gender equality risks overlooking alternative reforms—such as enhanced family support, workplace accommodation, or systemic aid for mothers—which some argue could better address root inequalities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Evictionism is a moral theory advanced by Walter Block and Roy Whitehead on a proposed libertarian view of abortion based on property rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] This theory is built upon the earlier work of philosopher Murray Rothbard who wrote that "no being has a right to live, unbidden, as a parasite within or upon some person's body" and that therefore the woman is entitled to eject the baby from her body at any time.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Evictionists view a woman's womb as her property and an unwanted fetus as a "trespasser or parasite", even while lacking the will to act.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] They argue that a pregnant woman has the right to evict a fetus from her body since she has no obligation to care for a trespasser.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The authors' hope is that bystanders will "homestead" the right to care for evicted babies and reduce the number of human deaths.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Building on the libertarian stand against trespass and murder, Block supports a right to the first act (eviction), but not the second act (murder).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] 2. the woman has publicly announced her abandonment of the right to custody of the fetus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some activists and academics, such as Andrea Smith, argue that the criminalization of abortion furthers the marginalization of oppressed groups such as poor women and women of color.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Sending these women into the prison system would do nothing to address the social/political/economic problems that marginalize these women or, sometimes, cause them to require abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some argue that race and sex-based abortions being prohibited further marginalizes oppressed groups by criminalizing those aspects of abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Anthony and Frederick Douglas Prenatal Nondiscrimination Act, proposed in Arizona in 2011, prohibited race and sex-based abortions and allowed punishment for those who perform abortions based on that criteria.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The bill characterized sex-based abortions as sex-based infanticide, and abortions based on the race of the fetus, or the race of the parent of the fetus, were seen as a practice that reinforces aspects of racial discrimination.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Laws like these can be seen as heightening the racialization of certain issues surrounding abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] According to the WHO, criminalization can have a major negative impact on "the provision of quality care" by preventing medical personnel from acting out of fear of retaliation or punishment.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The 2022 LTP Evaluation found that doctors were unwilling to conduct late abortions even when the legislation allowed them, preferring to refer pregnant women to clinics abroad out of anxiety for the possibility of exposing themselves to criminal culpability.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] This worry even extends to an unfounded fear of being prosecuted for sending their patient to a clinic in a different country where late abortion is permitted.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The criminalization of abortion in certain states has forced women to cross state lines for abortion care.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] It was found that women living in states with more hostile abortion laws were traveling out of state for abortion care in greater percentages than women living in states with protected abortion access.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] This also brought about the term "abortion deserts", which are locations or counties that have no abortion facilities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] People traveling interstate for abortions decrease their home state's abortion rates, but it increases the percentages of women who will need to travel across state lines to get access to abortion care.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] The travel also comes with other costs, such as transportation, insurance costs, missing work, childcare, etc. that impact the people who need this abortion care.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] These burdens tend to disproportionately affect people of color and impoverished people in need of reproductive healthcare.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Abortion criminalization also affects abortion providers by placing strict regulations and requirements on the providers.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Targeted Regulation of Abortion Provider laws (TRAP laws) are state laws that impose annual licensing fees, personnel or facility mandates, etc. on facilities that want to continue to be abortion providers; these regulations are not imposed on other similar clinics or facilities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some criticize these laws as excessive, with many of the regulations seeming excessive.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Some states have requirements for room sizes and ceiling heights, room temperatures, procedure supervision, etc. that may make it harder for facilities to acquire licensure or hard for physicians to perform the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Research has been conducted exploring whether banning abortion reduces abortion rates.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Researchers from the Guttmacher Institute, the World Health Organization, and the University of Massachusetts concluded that, in countries where abortions were restricted, the number of unintended pregnancies increased.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Even where abortions are illegal, they continue to take place, however, they are generally done unsafely, both because the need for secrecy tends to be more important than the woman's safety, and due to the lack of training and experience the person performing the abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] When done correctly by properly trained doctors, abortion is generally safe.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] Where laws restrict abortion rights, abortions are less safe and result in the deaths of 30,000 women each year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p01] It has been suggested that access to abortion can help reduce human overpopulation, which is shown to be harmful to the natural environment.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The book *Abortion and the Conscience of the Nation* (1983) presented the argument that abortion involves unjust discrimination against the unborn.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] According to this argument, those who deny that fetuses have a right to life do not value *all* human life, but instead, select arbitrary characteristics (such as particular levels of physical or psychological development) as giving some human beings more value or rights than others.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Some abortion opponents have argued for, and promoted legislation for, a ban on the abortion of fetuses that have been diagnosed with Down syndrome on the basis that such abortions unfairly discriminate against disabled people.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Critics of these measures charge that they are hypocritical since many of their proponents appear to be unconcerned with addressing the needs of living disabled persons.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The argument of deprivation states that abortion is morally wrong because it deprives the fetus of a valuable future.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] On this account, killing an adult human being is wrong because it deprives the victim of a "future like ours"—a future containing highly valuable or desirable experiences, activities, projects, and enjoyments.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] If a being has such a future, then killing that being would seriously harm the fetus and hence would be seriously wrong.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] According to the argument, since a fetus does have such a future, the "overwhelming majority" of deliberate abortions are placed in the "same moral category" as killing an innocent adult human being.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Not all abortions are unjustified according to this argument; abortion would be justified if the same justification could be applied to killing an adult human.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Criticism of this line of reasoning follows several threads.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Some reject the argument on grounds relating to personal identity, holding that the fetus is "not the same entity" as the adult into which it will develop, and thus that the fetus does not have a "future like ours" in the required sense.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Some anti-abortion supporters argue that if there is uncertainty as to whether the fetus has a right to life, then having an abortion is equivalent to consciously taking the risk of killing another.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] According to this argument, if it is not known for certain whether something (such as the fetus) has a right to life, then it is reckless and morally wrong to treat that thing as if it *lacks* a right to life (for example by killing it).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] This would place abortion in the same moral category as manslaughter (if it turns out that the fetus has a right to life) or certain forms of criminal negligence (if it turns out that the fetus does not have a right to life).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] David Boonin replies that if this kind of argument were correct, then the killing of nonhuman animals and plants would also be morally wrong because Boonin contends it is not known for certain that such beings lack a right to life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A primary slippery slope argument used against the practice of abortion claims that the continuity of human life from conception onward requires that we do not arbitrarily deny life prior to any particular developmental milestone.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] For otherwise, it would be a slippery slope to the denial of adult human being's right to life because there would only be an arbitrary difference between the two cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Thus the argument concludes that the only non-arbitrary and fair point at which to distinguish when human life has a stringent right to life and when it does not is at conception.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Another argument used by anti-abortion activists is the slippery slope argument, that normalizing abortion may lead to the normalization of other practices such as euthanasia.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Some anti-abortion activists argue that having an abortion can cause long-term harm to a woman's emotional and physical health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Views from different religions can often be in direct opposition to each other.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Muslims typically cite the Quranic verse 17:31 which states that a fetus should not be aborted out of fear of poverty.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Christians who oppose abortion support their views with Scripture references such as that of Luke 1:15; Jeremiah 1:4–5; Genesis 25:21–23; Matthew 1:18; and Psalm 139:13–16.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The Roman Catholic Church, Eastern Orthodox Church and Oriental Orthodox Churches, constituting approximately 70% of Christians worldwide, believe that human life begins at conception, as does the right to life; thus, abortion is considered immoral.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Most Evangelical Christians also consider abortion to be immoral.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The Church of England also considers abortion to be morally wrong, though their position admits abortion when "the continuance of a pregnancy threatens the life of the mother".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Further, they argue that if women did not have easy access to abortions, governments would be forced to invest more money into supporting mothers.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Other feminists oppose abortion because it distracts from other women's issues.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Some feminists have argued that abortion is inconsistent with feminist principles of justice and opposition to discrimination and violence.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Some feminists see abortion as an excuse for men to not take responsibility for sexually exploiting women because abortion prevents men from having to take care of any children the woman has as a result of the sexual intercourse.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Turning this argument around, the principle of equal rights and responsibilities, along with biological parents' responsibility toward their born children, implies that either the right to abortion or the right not to be coerced into abortion does not exist.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The Mexico City policy is a U.S. federal government policy requiring any non-governmental organization that is based outside the U.S. and receives U.S. government funding to refrain from performing or promoting abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] It is known by critics as the "global gag rule".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Bush, suspended again by President Barack Obama on 24 January 2009 and re-instated once again by President Donald Trump on 23 January 2017.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In 2021, President Biden rescinded the Mexico City policy, and on January 24, 2025, President Donald Trump reinstated the Mexico City Policy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A number of opinion polls around the world have explored public opinion regarding the issue of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Results have varied from poll to poll, country to country, and region to region, while varying with regard to different aspects of the issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A November 2005 poll in Mexico found that 73.4% think abortion should not be legalized while 11.2% think it should be.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A May 2024 poll in Canada found that a majority of Canadians (80%) are in favour of a woman's right to an abortion if she so chooses, while around one in ten (11%) are opposed, and 9% do not know where they stand on the matter.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A May 2005 survey examined attitudes toward abortion in 10 European countries, asking respondents whether they agreed with the statement, "If a woman doesn't want children, she should be allowed to have an abortion".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The highest level of approval was 81% (in the Czech Republic); the lowest was 47% (in Poland).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In 2019, 58% of Poles supported abortion on request up to the 12th week of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A 2021 study showed that abortion providers faced discrimination and termination in the workplace, death threats, harassment, and impacts to their private and personal lives for them and their families.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The same study shows that the providers continue to work in the field due to their commitment to women's health and pro-choice cause.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] As of 2022, after the overturn of *Roe vs Wade* by the Supreme Court, a *Wall Street Journal* poll conducted in March showed that 60% of voters believed that abortion should be legal in most cases, an increase of 5% earlier in the year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] 29% of participates believed it should be illegal in most cases, except for endangerment of the woman, rape, or incest.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Lastly, 6% said it should be illegal in all cases, down from 11% earlier that same year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A 2024 Pew Research Center poll reported 63% of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The poll found that the share of Americans living in states with abortion bans or restrictions who believe abortions should be easier to access has increased by 12%.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] This poll found little difference based on gender (61% of men generally supportive vs 64% of women) with education and especially religious affiliation being better predictive factors.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] It also shows that younger people tend to be more positive towards abortion with the 50-64 group being the most negative.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] African countries have different views based on region and cultural influences.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In Kenya, both male and female opinions show that abortion is frowned upon, due to embedded social norms that stem from religious and cultural beliefs.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] While younger generations are starting to normalize abortions, limited access to procedure, high costs, and lack of information still leads to unsafe abortion practices.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In Nigeria, the abortion laws are even stricter.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Rather than being ostracized by the community, abortion in Nigeria can lead to life imprisonment for both the abortion seekers and those who assist them.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The country's government has outlawed abortion in all cases except to save the life of the pregnant person.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In a survey of women, many cited religion, incomplete abortion, future infertility, and death as a fear when seeking abortion in Nigeria.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Of attitudes in South America, a December 2003 survey found that 30% of Argentines thought that abortion in Argentina should be allowed "regardless of situation", 47% that it should be allowed "under some circumstances", and 23% that it should not be allowed "regardless of situation".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A subsequent poll suggested that 45% of Argentinians are in favor of abortion for any reason in the first twelve weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] This same poll conducted in September 2011 also suggests that most Argentinians favor abortion being legal when a woman's health or life is at risk (81%), when the pregnancy is a result of rape (80%) or the fetus has severe abnormalities (68%).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A March 2007 poll regarding the abortion law in Brazil found that 65% of Brazilians believe that it "should not be modified", 16% that it should be expanded "to allow abortion in other cases", 10% that abortion should be "decriminalized", and 5% were "not sure".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Later a poll made in September 2022 found that the 70% of Brazilians were against abortions, 20% were in favor of it, 8% were neither in favor or against it, and 2% didn't know what to answer.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A July 2005 poll in Colombia found that 65.6% said they thought that abortion should remain illegal, 26.9% that it should be made legal, and 7.5% that they were unsure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] More secular parts of Asia such as Japan and Taiwan are more likely to favor abortion, and more religious parts such as Pakistan and Indonesia are more likely to oppose abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Other countries, such as China, are in between but still slightly favoring abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] According to global surveys in 2023 and 2024, the right to access legal abortion is widely supported.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] There is particularly strong widespread support for legal abortion in Europe.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] More than one in two (56%) across 29 countries believe abortion should be legal, including more than one in four (27%) who feel it should be legal in all cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Support for abortion is highest in Europe, with Sweden and France having the highest level of sentiment in believing abortion should be legal (87% and 82% respectively).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Support is lowest in Asia, with Indonesia and Malaysia the only countries where less than one in three think abortion should be legal (22% and 29% respectively).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A theory attempts to draw a correlation between the United States' unprecedented nationwide decline of the overall crime rate during the 1990s and the decriminalization of abortion 20 years prior.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The suggestion was brought to widespread attention by a 1999 academic paper, *The Impact of Legalized Abortion on Crime*, authored by the economists Steven D.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] They attributed the drop in crime to a reduction in individuals said to have a higher statistical probability of committing crimes: unwanted children, especially those born to mothers who are African American, impoverished, adolescent, uneducated, and single.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The change coincided with what would have been the adolescence, or peak years of potential criminality, of those who had not been born as a result of *Roe v Wade* and similar cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Donohue and Levitt's study also noted that states which legalized abortion before the rest of the nation experienced the lowering crime rate pattern earlier, and those with higher abortion rates had more pronounced reductions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Levitt and Donohue responded to this by presenting an adjusted data set which took into account these concerns and reported that the data maintained the statistical significance of their initial paper.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Such research has been criticized by some as being utilitarian, discriminatory as to race and socioeconomic class, and as promoting eugenics as a solution to crime.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Levitt states in his book *Freakonomics* that they are neither promoting nor negating any course of action—merely reporting data as economists.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The abortion–breast cancer hypothesis posits that induced abortion may increase the risk of developing breast cancer.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] This 1980's paper actually contrasts with other scientific data that abortion is not related causality with breast cancer occurrence.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The hypothesis mechanism was explored in rat studies conducted in the 1980s, from the same lab, so it lacks any scientific validation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Many states require an unmarried minor to have parental consent or notification before an abortion is allowed to happen.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] These are known as parental involvement laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The parents or guardians of the pregnant person must be consulted before an abortion is to be induced legally.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] States with these laws generally have different degrees of involvement and enforcement.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] A judge can be consulted to overrule a parent in the event the pregnant person is denied abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Studies have shown that these the required notification laws have not affected the probability that teenagers will engage in sexual activity or the demand for abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The rate of abortions for minors decreases in states with parental involvement laws by nearly 13 to 22 percent, however, it raises the rate for out-of-state abortions such in the case of Mississippi and Missouri.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Teenagers are shown to seek abortion across state lines to areas with less restrictive abortion laws to bypass these preventative methods.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In the United States, 37 states require the parent to have knowledge while only 21 of those states need one parent to consent.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Certain states have an alternative answer to the involvement of the parent by getting the judicial system involved with a judicial bypass.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In those states, minors can get permission from the judge if parents are not willing to do so or if they are absent from their lives.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] There are different guidelines for minors and abortions in every country.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] In most of Europe, all persons that are capable of judgment enjoy medical privacy and can decide medical matters on their own.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] The capability of judgment does not come at a defined age, however, and is dependent on how well the person is able to understand the decision and its consequences.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] For most medical procedures, the capability of judgment usually sets in at ages 12 to 14.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Parental involvement is one of the most common methods of restricting abortion, along with Medicaid funding restrictions, mandatory delay laws, licensing fees for abortion providers, and mandatory counseling laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] Economist Marshall Medoff has argued that parental involvement laws are largely ineffective at reducing abortion demands.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-debate-p02] One cause could be that some states do not require parental involvement, so out-of-state abortions could meet the demands.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Abortion was deemed illegal under the Penal Code of 1886.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Convictions were all but precluded, however, by a requirement that the prosecution prove that the fetus had been alive until the abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The Morality Acts of 1911 closed this loophole, and strictly barred all abortions, except those performed to save the life of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Legalization reached the forefront of public debate in the Netherlands during the 1970s as many other Western European countries liberalized their laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The Staten-Generaal, however, was unable to reach a consensus between those opposing legalization, those in favor of allowing abortion, and those favoring a compromise measure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] A controversial abortion law was passed in 1981 with single swing votes: 76 for and 74 against in the House of Representatives, and 38 for and 37 against in the Senate.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The law left abortion a crime, unless performed at a clinic or hospital that is issued an official abortion certificate by the Dutch government, and the woman who is asking for the abortion declares she considers it to be an emergency.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The law came into effect on 1 November 1984.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Currently, there are just over 100 Dutch general hospitals certified to perform abortions, and 17 specialized abortion clinics.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] More than 90% of abortions take place in the specialized clinics.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] In the Netherlands, abortion performed by a certified clinic or hospital is effectually allowed at any point between conception and viability, till 2022 subject to a five-day waiting period.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The waiting period does not apply if the menstrual period is less than 17 days overdue (very early stage pregnancy).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] After the first trimester, the procedure becomes stricter, as two doctors must consent to treatment.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] In practice, abortions are performed until approximately 24 weeks into pregnancy, although this limit is the topic of ongoing discussion among physicians in the Netherlands, since, due to recent medical advancements, a fetus can sometimes be considered viable prior to 24 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] As a result of this debate, abortions are only rarely performed after 22 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Abortions must be performed in a hospital.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Abortion in the Netherlands can completed with the use of different procedures including use of an abortion pill, vacuum aspiration, or dilation and evacuation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Since February 2000, the use of the abortion pill was legalized in the Netherlands.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The pills are permitted to be taken up to 49 days after the first day of the last menstrual bleed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] For most people, this is a timeframe of approximately three weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] For this procedure, you get prescribed three pills.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The pills need to be taken during an in-clinic appointments.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] With your last appointment you are required to stay for 4–6 hours for observation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] This is a procedure that uses a vacuum or suction device as a source to remove an embryo or fetus from the womb.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] This procedure is only available in certified medical clinics or hospitals.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] This is a surgical procedure that is offered after the first trimester of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] This procedure completely removes the fetus and all placental tissue in the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] An other name for this procedure are surgical abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] Sometimes this procedure is also used in case of an incomplete miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] The number of abortions has been relatively stable in the 21st century, around 28,000 per year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] As of 2010, the abortion rate was 9.7 abortions per 1000 women aged 15–44 years (0.97%), one of the lowest in the world.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] 1 in 5 women in the Netherlands has experience with an unwanted pregnancy, however, only 13.5% of those unwanted pregnancies end with an abortion (as of 2015).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-in-the-netherlands] However, since scrapping the mandatory 5-days wait period (rule went into effect in January 2023), abortion number has raised.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Public health researchers and organizations have also framed access to legal abortion as a public health measure, given its association with reduced maternal mortality.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] China, which has ended its one-child policy and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of its population control strategy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The issue of induced abortion remains divisive in public life, with recurring arguments to liberalize or restrict access to legal abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Some abortion-rights supporters are divided as to the types of abortion services that should be available under different circumstances, including periods in the pregnancy such as late term abortions, in which access may or may not be restricted.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Many of the terms used in the debate are political framing terms used to validate one's stance while invalidating the opposition.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] For example, the labels pro-choice and pro-life imply endorsement of widely held values such as liberty and freedom, while suggesting that the opposition must be "anti-choice" or "anti-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These views do not always align along a strict binary.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In one poll conducted by the Public Religion Research Institute, the ambiguity of the terms led 70% of Americans to identify as 'pro-choice,' while nearly two-thirds simultaneously identified as "pro-life".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] It was found that, in polling, respondents would label themselves differently when given specific details about the circumstances around an abortion including factors such as rape, incest, viability of the fetus, and survivability of the mother.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Associated Press favors the terms "abortion rights" and "anti-abortion" instead.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion practices date back to 1550 BCE, based on the findings of practices recorded on documents.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion has been an active practice since Egyptian medicine.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Centuries later, abortion was a topic taken up by feminism.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Mohr, there was an earlier acceptance of abortion, and opposition to abortion, including anti-abortion laws, only came into being in the 19th century.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] It was not always a crime and was generally not illegal until quickening, which occurred between the fourth and sixth months of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In the 19th century, the medical profession was generally opposed to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Mohr argues that the opposition arose due to competition between men with medical degrees and women without one, such as Madame Drunette.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The practice of abortion was one of the first medical specialities, and was practiced by unlicensed people; well-off people had abortions and paid well.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The press played a key role in rallying support for anti-abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The ideas of the legalization of abortion in the late 19th century were often opposed by feminists, seeing it as a means of relieving men of responsibility.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In *The Revolution*, which was an official published newspaper of women's rights that went out weekly, operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Anthony, an anonymous contributor signing "A" wrote in 1869 about the subject, arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] *The Revolution* newspaper highly impacted the women's rights movement, and for the first time, it seemed like women's voices were being heard through the proclamations of these unacknowledged subjects regarding women and their everyday rights and safety as citizens.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The writer wrote that simply passing an anti-abortion law would "be only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels, including prescriptions and procedures.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The only exception for a woman to get an abortion without fear of legal retribution was if a licensed physician determined the abortion would protect the mother's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Physicians who provide abortions and women who have abortions were constantly harassed by courts and prosecutors.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes with the abortion law.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the abortion laws.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should provide exemptions for women that were sexually assaulted or for a baby that may not have a good quality of life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The abortion-rights movement became a controversial topic in the United States regarding abortion and reproduction.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The movement towards the liberalization of abortion law emerged in the 1920s and 1930s in the context of the victories that had been recently won in the area of birth control.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Campaigners including Marie Stopes in England and Margaret Sanger in the US had succeeded in bringing the issue into the open, and birth control clinics were established that offered family planning advice and contraceptive methods to women in need.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Birth control is a method of pregnancy prevention through controlled contraception.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1929, the Infant Life Preservation Act was passed in the United Kingdom, which amended the law (Offences against the Person Act 1861) so that an abortion carried out in good faith, for the sole purpose of preserving the life of the mother, would not be an offense.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Many citizens had mixed opinions on this, but ultimately started protesting this as child destruction.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Child destruction was known as taking the life of a viable unborn child during a pregnancy or at birth, before it is independent of its mother.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] If there is an intent of death and no good faith is carried out in the process in order to protect the mother's livelihood, the offense carries a maximum punishment of life imprisonment.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Infant Life Preservation Act defines the difference between murder and abortion-the causing of a miscarriage.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Stella Browne was a leading birth control campaigner, who increasingly began to venture into the more contentious issue of abortion in the 1930s.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Browne's beliefs were heavily influenced by the work of Havelock Ellis, Edward Carpenter and other sexologists.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] She came to strongly believe that working women should have the choice to become pregnant and to terminate their pregnancy while they worked in the horrible circumstances surrounding a pregnant woman who was still required to do hard labor during her pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In this case she argued that doctors should give free information about birth control to women that wanted to know about it.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This would give women agency over their own circumstances and allow them to decide whether they wanted to be mothers or not.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These talks urged women to take matters of their sexuality and their health into their own hands.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] She became increasingly interested in her view of the woman's right to terminate their pregnancies, and in 1929, she brought forward her lecture "The Right to Abortion" in front of the World Sexual Reform Congress in London.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1931, Browne began to develop her argument for women's right to decide to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] She again began touring, giving lectures on abortion and the negative consequences that followed if women were unable to terminate pregnancies of their own choosing such as: suicide, injury, permanent invalidism, madness and blood-poisoning.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] On February 17, 1936, Janet Chance, Alice Jenkins and Joan Malleson established the Abortion Law Reform Association as the first advocacy organization for abortion liberalization.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The association promoted access to abortion in the United Kingdom and campaigned for the elimination of legal obstacles.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In its first year ALRA recruited 35 members, and by 1939 had almost 400 members.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The ALRA was very active between 1936 and 1939 sending speakers around the country to talk about Labour and Equal Citizenship and attempted, though most often unsuccessfully, to have letters and articles published in newspapers.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] They became the most popular when a member of the ALRA's Medico-Legal Committee received the case of a fourteen-year-old girl who had been raped, and received a termination of this pregnancy from Dr.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Joan Malleson, a progenitor of the ALRA.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1938, Joan Malleson precipitated one of the most influential cases in British abortion law when she referred a pregnant fourteen-year old rape survivor to gynaecologist Aleck Bourne.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] He performed an abortion, then illegal, and was put on trial on charges of procuring abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Bourne was eventually acquitted in *R v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Bourne*as his actions were "...an example of disinterested conduct in consonance with the highest traditions of the profession".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This court case set a precedent that doctors could not be prosecuted for performing an abortion in cases where pregnancy would probably cause "mental and physical wreck".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Abortion Law Reform Association continued its campaigning after the Second World War, and this, combined with broad social changes brought the issue of abortion back into the political arena in the 1960s.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In America an abortion reform movement emerged in the 1960s.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion and her photo became the symbol of the abortion rights movement.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The landmark judicial ruling of the Supreme Court in *Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Wade* ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This was back in 1970, where Jane Roe, (which was actually a fictional name used in the court documents in order to protect the plaintiff's identity), had filed a lawsuit against Henry Wade.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] He was the district attorney of Dallas County in Texas, where Jane Roe resided.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] She was challenging a Texas law making abortion illegal except by a doctor's orders to save a woman's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right to privacy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being in the decision *Doe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] From the 1970s, and the spread of second-wave feminism, abortion and reproductive rights became unifying issues among various women's rights groups in Canada, the United States, the Netherlands, Britain, Norway, France, Germany, and Italy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 2015, in the wake of the House of Representatives' vote to defund Planned Parenthood, Lindy West, Amelia Bonow and Kimberly Morrison launched ShoutYourAbortion to "remind supporters and critics alike abortion is a legal right to anyone who wants or needs it".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 2019, the You Know Me movement started as a response to the successful 2019 passage of fetal heartbeat bills in five states in the United States, most notably the passing of anti-abortion laws in Georgia (House Bill 381), Ohio (House Bill 68) and Alabama (House Bill 314).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This movement was started off by actress Busy Philipps because she had previously had an abortion when she was a teen.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The actress and many others believe that it is important for women to speak up and shift the narrative, especially because abortion is such a taboo subject.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In the mid-19th century, concerns around abortion only consisted of the danger of a woman being poisoned and risking her health, not because of religion, ethics, or diplomacy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Ending a pregnancy before the fetus began movement, or "post-quickening" was only a wrongdoing, not a crime.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The laws that were against abortions post-quickening removals were put in place to protect the well-being of the women that were pregnant, not the fetal life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] It was more common for women to die during early terminations due to the usage of pre-owned instruments as opposed to natural abortifacients.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Some women who engaged in quickening abortions were not prosecuted because there was no evidence and quickening was hard to prove.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels included the prescription of drugs or undergoing procedures.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The only exception for a woman to proceed with an abortion without worrying about breaking any anti-abortion laws is if a licensed physician were to prove that the abortion was for the protection of the mother's life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion care providers and women who had obtained an abortion were pestered by courts and prosecutors.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes, around the abortion law, from their states.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the fetus removal laws that were put in place.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should exempt women that were sexually assaulted, whose babies well-being were to be questioned and whose babies that were to be born out of its true, natural or original state.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Abortion Rights Movement became a cultural shift in The United States about the intentions of reproduction and abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Wade* verdict changed the abortion laws altogether, making abortion legal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Many physicians and healthcare professionals jeopardized their medical licenses, risked being put in prison and fined by the state because they wanted to continue to provide abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] There were more than 1,000 abortion laws passed and enacted between 2011 and 2019 that limited access to abortion procedures.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Some of these laws forbid a woman getting an abortion past a certain gestational age and was also based on race and specific pregnancy conditions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Other laws were established that ban particular abortion methods.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Targeted regulation of abortion providers (TRAP) was put in place to target abortion clinics by demanding unnecessary requirements that made it hard for women to get an abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Opponents of abortion rights claim that these requirements are for the safety of the mother and child, but that has not been scientifically proven.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] TRAP has placed limitations on abortion facilities to make it more difficult for them to provide abortion services that will essentially force them to not provide abortion services at all.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] TRAP policies have been put in place by 26 states as of 2020.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] During the pandemic, numerous states prohibited non-essential medical procedures, including abortion services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Policymakers in twelve states saw this as a chance to certify abortion as non-essential, therefore ending services.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Jackson Women's Health Organization overturned Roe v.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Wade, removing the federal constitutional right to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This left abortion laws and restrictions up to each individual state.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] South Africa allows abortion on demand under its Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Most African nations, however, have abortion bans except in cases where the woman's life or health is at risk.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] A number of abortion-rights international organizations have made altering abortion laws and expanding family planning services in sub-Saharan Africa and the developing world a top priority.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] But there are only five countries in Africa where abortion is legal and those countries are Cape Verde, South Africa, Tunisia, Mozambique and Saõ Tome & Principe.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] 8.2 million abortions were performed each year in Africa.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This number increased drastically compared to the 4.6 million abortions that were performed during 1990–1994.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] But this increased number of abortions is due to the increase of women that are reproducing at a young age.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Approximately 93% of women within their reproductive age live in countries that have very restrictive abortion laws and abortion is only legal in 10 out of 54 African countries, leading to fewer women not being able to obtain a safe procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The World Health Organization only recommends trained personnel when performing induced abortions but not many women in Africa have access to trained professionals who are able to provide them with the best service to decrease the number of complications due to abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Approximately 1.6 million women are treated for abortion-related complications and only one in four abortions in Africa are safe.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Africa has the highest number of deaths that are related to abortion and this is due to the most common complication of abortion that consist of excessive blood loss and an incomplete abortion that can lead to an infection.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] During 2010–2014, 36 million abortions were performed in Asia.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Majority of abortions occurred in Central and South Asia at a rate of 16 million in India and Asia and 13 million in China alone.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Although the abortions performed in Asia are not known, there is an estimated 4.6 million women who are treated because they have complications due to the performance of an unsafe abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The major complication of abortion is an incomplete abortion where a woman can experience an immoderate amount of blood loss and can develop an infection.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Less common complications of abortion include a woman going into septic shock, damaging the internal organs and causing the peritoneum to be inflamed, all due to the unclean and unsterilized instruments that are being used doing the procedure.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Untreated complications from abortions can leave women to experience negative health consequences for life that include infertility, chronic pain, inflammation of the reproductive organs and pelvic inflammatory disease.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Unsafe abortions go deeper than just a woman's health but they lead to reduced productivity for women increased costs to an already struggling family.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Although it is not completely known, a drug known as misoprostol is used to perform abortions in Asian countries and evidence shows that the sales of this drug has increased in Asia over the course of years.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] On record, out of all the pregnancies in Asia, 27 percent of them end in abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This is the reason for the Asia Safe Abortion Partnership (ASAP).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This program was formed to increase the accessibility to safe and legal abortions and health care that is needed after any abortion service.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] 50 countries occupy Asia and out of those 50, 17 countries do not have a restriction on abortions excluding, gestational limits and permission from a spouse or parent.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] ASAP satisfies the demand for safe and accessible abortions through educational and advocacy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] By grouping with other countries to promote advocacy networks, ASAP has created a worldwide and generational feminist power that advocates for women's abortion rights, autonomy and dignity.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Anti-abortion groups have tried their best to discriminate the reproductive autonomy of women but ASAP has members spread across 20 countries that promote the women's movement for abortion rights, laws, and access.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Even though abortion is legal in Asia, that does not mean that women always have access or adequate health care during these times.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] For example, abortions in India have been legal since 1951 but women who are particularly poor or marginalized make up 50% of unsafe abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Women in the Philippines are more than likely to undergo an unsafe and unsanitary abortion causing around 1,000 death annually due to abortion complications.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Philippines along with Iraq and Laos are the countries that has not made abortion legal, excluding legal exceptions, therefore they have not made it available to where women can have admissions to legal abortions that are safe for them and their bodies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Countries such as Afghanistan, Thailand, China and Lebanon, have all been impacted by the determined long-term feminist motion by ASAP for women's abortion rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This work ranges from workshops, journalists, advocates to menstrual management, violence against women, and issues surrounded unplanned pregnancies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] "Youth champions" were created by ASAP to share the knowledge that they have learned to their peers about sexual activity, abortions, women's rights and reproductions, reproductive health, and the abortion rights movement in general.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Chapter XXIX of the Penal Code of Japan makes abortion illegal in Japan.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Other people, including the mother herself, trying to abort the fetus can be punished by the law.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] People trying to practice abortion without the consent of the woman can also be punished, including the doctors.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion has been illegal in South Korea since 1953 but on April 11, 2019, South Korea's Constitutional Court ruled the abortion ban unconstitutional and called for the law to be amended.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Constitutional Court has taken into consideration abortion-rights cases by women because they find the abortion ban as unconstitutional.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] To help support the legalization of abortion in South Korea, thousands of advocates compiled a petition for the Blue House to consider lifting the ban.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Due to the abortion ban, this has led to many dangerous self-induced abortions and other illegal practices of abortion that needs more attention.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] This is why there are advocates challenging the law to put into perspective the negative factors this abortion ban brings.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] By making abortion illegal in South Korea, this also creates an issue when it comes to women's rights and their own rights to their bodies.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] As a result, many women's advocate groups were created and acted together to protest against the abortion ban law.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Global Day of Action is a form of protest that advocates to make a change and bring more awareness to global warming.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] During this protest, a group of feminist Korean advocates called, "The Joint Action for Reproductive Justice" connected with one another to promote concerns that requires more attention and needs a quick change such as making abortion legal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] By combining different advocate groups that serves different purposes and their own goals they want to achieve into one event, it helps promote all the different aspects of reality that needs to change.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In 1920, under the leadership of Vladimir Lenin, Russia became the first country in the world to legally permit abortion, no matter the circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] But in the 20th century, the laws surrounding abortion were repeatedly modified between the years of 1936 and 1955.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] According to data from the United Nations in 2010, Russia had the highest rates of abortion per woman of reproduction.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Results from the abortion rates of China and Russia were compared and out of a population of 1.3 billion people, China only reported 13 million abortions, a huge difference when contrasted to the population in Russia of 143 million people with 1.2 million abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Since abortion was illegal in the Russian Empire, it was not recognized in the Domostroi.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Domostroi was a set of tasks that were to be followed that were structured around rules, instructions surrounded by religious, social and domestic issues that were centered within the Russian Society.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These rules enforced respect and compliance to God and the church.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Different rulers had different views about abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] During Romanov's reign, abortion was illegal, frowned up, and if a woman were to go through with an abortion, her punishment was death.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] But after Romanov's reign ended, Peter the Great lifted the punishment of death for abortions but it was still considered a serious issue in 1917.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Before the punishment for abortions was death, according to the Russian Penal Code that dates back to 1462–1463, women were dispossessed of their basic human and civil rights and banned from the city or they were forced into hard labor.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These harsh treatments and illegality surrounded around abortion still did not stop women from pursuing abortions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] "Black Market" abortions were known as unauthorized and discreet procedures done by women who have experience in childbirth.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] These women were known as older women that were midwives and rural midwives, respectfully.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Although these women were not abortion care providers, they were the only accessible obstetric personnel that women could go to without facing the harsh punishment and consequences forced upon by the Russian Society.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Since adequate medical care was not provided for women looking to terminate their pregnancy, midwives and nurses from villages were trained to care for these women the best to their ability, but of course with illegal abortions there are always repercussions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] During the Soviet period in Russia, abortions ranked as the highest rates world-wide.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] After the Soviet period ended inn the Russian union, abortion numbers decreased with further enforced sex education courses and use of contraceptive birth control.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion was illegal in the Republic of Ireland except when the woman's life was threatened by a medical condition (including risk of suicide), since a 1983 referendum (aka 8th Amendment) amended the constitution.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Subsequent amendments in 1992 (after the X Case) – the thirteenth and fourteenth – guaranteed the right to travel abroad (for abortions) and to distribute and obtain information of "lawful services" available in other countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Two proposals to remove suicide risk as a ground for abortion were rejected by the people, in a referendum in 1992 and in 2002.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Thousands of women get around the ban by privately traveling to the other European countries (typically Britain and the Netherlands) to undergo termination, or by ordering abortion pills from Women on Web online and taking them in Ireland.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Sinn Féin, the Labour Party, Social Democrats, Green Party, Communist Party, Socialist Party and Irish Republican Socialist Party have made their official policies to support abortion rights.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Mainstream center-right parties such as Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael do not have official policies on abortion rights but allow their members to take a conscience vote in support of abortion in limited circumstances.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Aontú, founded in January 2019, is firmly anti-abortionist and seeks to "protect the right to life".
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] After the death of Savita Halappanavar in 2012, there has been a renewed campaign to repeal the eighth amendment and legalize abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] As of January 2017, the Irish government has set up a citizens assembly to look at the issue.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Their proposals, broadly supported by a cross-party Oireachtas committee, include repeal of the 8th Amendment, unrestricted access to abortion for the first 12 weeks of pregnancy and no-term limits for special cases of fatal foetal abnormalities, rape and incest.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] A referendum on the repealing of the 8th Amendment was held on May 25, 2018.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Together for Yes, a cross-society group formed from the Coalition to Repeal the 8th Amendment, the National Women's Council of Ireland and the Abortion Rights Campaign, were the official campaign group for repeal in the referendum.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Activists utilized social media to bring the narrative of women's voices to the forefront of the campaign, making clear that the Eighth Amendment was dangerous for pregnant women to try and encourage voters to vote in favor of repeal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The 67% majority in favor of repeal is a testament to these stories and the women who braved the public Twitter sphere to change the law around women's reproductive lives.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Despite being part of the United Kingdom, abortion remained illegal in Northern Ireland, except in cases when the woman is threatened by a medical condition, physical or mental, until 2019.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Women seeking abortions had to travel to England.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In October 2019, abortion up to 12 weeks was legalized, to begin in April 2020, but remains near-unobtainable.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Poland initially held abortion to be legal in 1958 by the communist government, but was later banned after restoration of democracy in 1989.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Currently, abortion is illegal in all cases except for rape or when the fetus or mother is in fatal conditions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The wide spread of Catholic Church in Poland within the country has made abortion socially 'unacceptable'.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Pope has had major influence on the acceptance of abortion within Poland.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Several landmark court cases have had substantial influence on the current status of abortion, including *Tysiac v Poland*.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act 1967 legalized abortion on a wide number of grounds, except in Northern Ireland.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] 4. shows there is evidence of extreme fetal abnormality i.e. the child would be seriously physically or mentally handicapped after birth and during life.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] However, the criterion of risk to mental and physical health is applied broadly, and *de facto* makes abortion available on demand, though this still requires the consent of two National Health Service doctors.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortions in Great Britain are provided at no out-of-pocket cost to the patient by the NHS.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats are predominantly pro-abortion-rights parties, though with significant minorities in each either holding more restrictive definitions of the right to choose, or subscribing to an anti-abortion analysis.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Conservative Party is more evenly split between both camps and its former leader, David Cameron, supports abortion on demand in the early stages of pregnancy.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion laws in the Middle East reflect variation of opinions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Some countries permit abortion in cases involving a pregnant woman's well-being, fetal impairment, and rape.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion was widely practiced during the colonial period, and allowed a longer term termination.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] By the 19th century, progressive interpretations cut the abortion time limit down to the first trimester.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] However, a 2008 World Health Organization report estimated 900,000 unsafe abortion occurred each year in the Middle Eastern and Northern Africa regions.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] While many countries have decriminalized abortions and made it more accessible, there are still a few remaining countries yet to do so.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] In April 2005, the Iranian Parliament approved a new bill easing the conditions by also allowing abortion in certain cases when the fetus shows signs of handicap.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Legal abortion is now allowed if the mother's life is in danger, and also in cases of fetal abnormalities that makes it not viable after birth (such as anencephaly) or produce difficulties for mother to take care of it after birth, such as major thalassemia or bilateral polycystic kidney disease.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Abortion-rights advocacy in the United States is centered in the United States abortion-rights movement.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Across the world, there are only four countries in which abortion is completely banned.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Honduras, Dominican Republic, Nicaragua, and El Salvador have yet to legalize abortions, even if it is for the woman's health and safety.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Since 2018, there have been no changes in the laws regarding abortion in these Latin-America countries.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Ministry of Public Health collected data that showed nearly half the pregnancies in the Dominican Republic alone are unwanted or unplanned; often stemming from incest or rape.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Women in South America continue fighting for their rights and protection, but there has been no recent call of action.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Because Argentina has been very restrictive against abortion, reliable reporting on abortion rates is unavailable.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Argentina has long been a strongly Catholic country, and protesters seeking legalized abortion in 2013 directed anger toward the Catholic Church.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] On December 11, 2020, after a 20-hour debate, the Chamber of Deputies voted 131 to 117 (6 abstentions) to approve a bill legalizing abortion up to 14 weeks after conception.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The bill's passing resulted in large-scale celebrations by abortion rights activists who had long campaigned for it.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] The Argentine Senate approved the bill 38–29 on December 29, and it is expected to be signed by President Alberto Fernandez.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/abortion-rights-movements] Argentina will become the fourth Latin American country to legalize abortion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The **AEX index**, derived from **Amsterdam Exchange index**, is a stock market index composed of Dutch companies that trade on Euronext Amsterdam, formerly known as the *Amsterdam Stock Exchange*.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Started in 1983, the index is composed of a maximum of 30 of the most frequently traded securities on the exchange.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] It is one of the main national indices of the stock exchange group Euronext alongside Euronext Brussels' BEL20, Euronext Dublin's ISEQ 20, Euronext Lisbon's PSI-20, the Oslo Bors OBX Index, and Euronext Paris's CAC 40.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The AEX started from a base level of 100 index points on 3 January 1983 (a corresponding value of 45.378 is used for historic comparisons due to the adoption of the Euro).
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The index's peak to date was set on 26 October 2021 816.91 After the dot-com bubble in 1999, the index value more than halved over the following three years before recovering in line with most global financial markets.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The AEX index dealt with its second largest one-day loss on 12 March 2020, when the index closed down almost 11% during the coronavirus pandemic.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The AEX index enjoyed its third largest one-day loss on 29 September 2008, when the index closed down almost 9%.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The decade between 1998 and 2008 was bad for the AEX index, as it was the worst performing stock index except for the OMX Iceland 15.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The preceding years were a lot better compared to the rest of the world.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The following table shows the annual development of the AEX index since 1983.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] As of 2011, the AEX index composition is reviewed four times a year - a full "annual" review in March and interim "quarterly" reviews in June, September and December.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Any changes made as a result of the reviews take effect on the third Friday of the month.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Previously reviews were held in March and September only.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Prior to 2008, index changes were made only annually in March.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] At the main March review date, the 23 companies listed on Euronext Amsterdam's regulated market with the highest share turnover (in Euros) over the previous year are admitted to the index.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Of the companies ranked between 24th and 27th, a further two are selected with preference given to existing constituents of the index.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Companies which have fewer than 25% of shares considered free float on Euronext Amsterdam are, however, ineligible for inclusion.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] Unlike some other European benchmark equity indices (such as the OMXS30), if a company has more than one class of shares traded on the exchange, only the most frequently traded of these will be accepted into the AEX.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] If a company or companies are removed from the index due to delisting, acquisition or another reason, no replacements are made until the next review date.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] At the three interim reviews in June, September and December, no changes are made to the AEX unless either the index has seen one or more constituents removed, or a non-constituent possesses a share turnover ranked 15th or higher overall over the previous 12 months.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] If vacancies are to be filled, the highest-ranking non-AEX companies are selected to join the index.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The AEX is a capitalization-weighted index.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] At each main annual review, the index weightings of companies in the index are capped at 15%, but range freely with share price subsequently.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The index weights are calculated with respect to the closing prices of the relevant companies on 1 March.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] At the interim reviews, weightings after adjustment are left as close as possible to those of the previous day and are not re-capped.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The index comprises a basket of shares, the numbers of which are based on the constituent weights and index value at the time of readjustment.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The AEX Index is traded as a future on the Euronext Equities & Index Derivatives exchange (EUREID) under the ticker symbol FTI.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The size of each contract is 200 EURO x AEX Index points (e.g.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/aex-index] The index is composed of the following listings as of 31 December 2024.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] When cwi.nl was registered by Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica on 1986-05-01, .nl became the first active ccTLD outside the United States.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Since 31 January 1996, .nl domains are registered by the Stichting Internet Domeinregistratie Nederland (SIDN, in English: Foundation for Internet Domain Registration Netherlands), based in Arnhem.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Most registrars are Internet service providers, IT service bureaus and media service bureaus, but several large enterprises with many brand names have also become a registrar, or participant as SIDN calls them, which is a quite uncommon phenomenon in the domain name industry.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Registrars have to pay SIDN a fee for each domain since 1 April 1996, until then registration was free.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] SIDN does not deal directly with registrants.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] In the early days, most of the registrants were universities and research departments of large companies, such as Philips Natuurkundig Laboratorium.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Besides .nl, SIDN also operates .politie in a partnership with the Dutch police and .amsterdam in cooperation with the municipality of Amsterdam and Dotlocal.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Official second-level domains do not exist.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] A number of companies have taken the opportunity to register domains like co.nl and com.nl, using them to sell third-level domains.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Individuals were allowed to register a second-level .nl domain since 2003.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] As a forerunner, individuals were allowed to register a third-level domain since 2000.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Such 'personal domains' had the form of janjansen.123.nl.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] They never became popular, and registration has been suspended since 2006.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Because there were only around 500 of such domains registered, in contrast to about 5 million second-level domains, SIDN announced the discontinuance of personal domains as of 2008 on 4 July 2007.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Unlike the majority of top level domains, .nl requires each nameserver to use a unique IP address.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] There must be at least two nameservers set, meaning at least two different IP addresses must be used.
[src:abortion-in-the-netherlands/nl] Other TLDs with this requirement are .ca and .cn.
